\begin_layout Section

Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "sec:intro"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Measuring several single grain U-Th-(Sm)-He aliquots per sample is not only possible, thanks to the development of laser heating 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "house2000"

\end_inset

, but also desirable, because U-Th-(Sm)-He data are generally overdispersed with respect to the formal analytical uncertainty and this overdispersion can only be quantified by analysing a representative number of mineral grains. The question then arises how to average these measurements. Traditionally, this is done by simply averaging the single grain age estimates, an 
\shape italic
ad hoc
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 solution that lacks a proper theoretical justification and does not make full use of the data. Potentially valuable information is lost when the chemical composition of samples is ignored, and compositional controls on thermochronological models may go unnoticed. The most natural way to study U-Th-(Sm)-He data is as a geochemical composition on a ternary diagram or in logratio space 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

.
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\family typewriter
HelioPlot
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 is a data visualisation tool that plots U-Th-(Sm)-He data on ternary diagrams and logratio plots. The program also calculates the so-called `central age', which is the age corresponding to the geometric mean U-Th-(Sm)-He composition. To this end, it applies a weighted mean algorithm taking into account both the analytical uncertainty and any possible overdispersion simultaneously, in contrast with 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

's web calculator, which propagated them separately. U-Th-(Sm)-He data are often overdispersed with respect to the analytical uncertainty, for reasons that have been discussed elsewhere 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "fitzgerald2006, shuster2006"

\end_inset

. The amount of overdispersion can be quantified using the Mean Square of the Weighted Deviates 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citep
after ""
before "MSWD, "
key "mcintyre1966"

\end_inset

. Given a dataset of n age measurements, or the logarithms thereof (t
\begin_inset Formula $_i$
\end_inset

, for 1
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

i
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

n), the MSWD is a measure of the ratio of the observed scatter of the data points (t
\begin_inset Formula $_i$
\end_inset

) around the mean value (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{t}$
\end_inset

) to the expected scatter from the assigned errors (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_i$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
MSWD = \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \frac{(t_i - \bar{t})^2}{\sigma_i^2}
\label{eq:MSWDt}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

If the assigned errors are the only cause of scatter, the MSWD will tend to be near unity. MSWD values much less than unity indicate either overestimated analytical errors or unrecognized error-correlations. MSWD values much greater than unity generally indicate either underestimated analytical errors, or the presence of non-analytical scatter. 
\family typewriter
HelioPlot
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 implements methods to deal with the latter situation.
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Although there is no formally agreed convention for calculating the average of multiple (U-Th)/He ages, this is either done by computing the unweighted arithmetic mean, ignoring the analytical precision, or by calculating the error-weighted mean, ignoring overdispersion. Section\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ages"

\end_inset

 introduces a one-dimensional weighted mean algorithm that deals with analytical precision and overdispersion simultaneously, using the method of maximum likelihood. Section\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:compositions"

\end_inset

 generalises this method to compositional data space, so as to calculate the best estimate for the central age, taking into account both the internal and external reproducibilities of the data, as well as their full covariance structure. `Conventional' propagation of uncertainty for the central age, as implemented by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

, involves linearisation by a first-order Maclaurin series expansion, which may be inaccurate. Section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ci"

\end_inset

 proposes a deterministic algorithm to avoid this problem, yielding exact confidence intervals for the central age. Finally, Section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:helioplot"

\end_inset

 provides further details about 
\family typewriter
HelioPlot
\family default
\series default
\shape default
 and illustrates its usefulness with a number of real world examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Overdispersed ages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "sec:ages"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Assume that the ages (or the logarithm of the ages) come from a normal distribution of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
  \label{eq:norm1}
  t_i \sim N(\mu,\sigma_i^2 + \xi^2)
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 denotes the mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi^2$
\end_inset

 is the amount of 
\shape italic
overdispersion
\family default
\series default
\shape default
, i.e. the excess scatter that cannot be explained by the analytical uncertainty alone. Unbiased estimates 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\xi}^2$
\end_inset

 for these two parameters can be obtained by maximising the likelihood l:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
l \equiv \prod_{i=1}^n 
\frac{exp\left(-\frac{(t_i - \hat{\mu})^2}
{2(\sigma_i^2 + \hat{\xi^2_i})}\right)}
{\sqrt{2\pi(\sigma_i^2 + \hat{\xi}^2)}}
  \label{eq:l1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

or, more conveniently, the log-likelihood L 
\begin_inset Formula $\equiv$
\end_inset

 log(l):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L = - \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^n 
\left[
\frac{(t_i - \hat{\mu})^2}{\sigma_i^2+\hat{\xi}^2}
+ ln(\sigma_i^2 + \hat{\xi}^2) + ln(2\pi)
\right]
  \label{eq:L1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

Calculating the derivatives of L with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\xi}^2$
\end_inset

 and setting them to zero to find the maximum likelihood:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
& \frac{\partial L}{\partial \hat{\mu}}  = 
\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{t_i - \hat{\mu}}{\sigma_i^2 + \hat{\xi}^2} = 0
\label{eq:Lmu1}\\
&\frac{\partial L}{\partial \hat{\xi}^2}  =
\sum_{i=1}^n \left[ \frac{(t_i-\hat{\mu})^2}{(\sigma_i^2+\hat{\xi}^2)^2}
- \frac{1}{\sigma_i^2+\hat{\xi}^2} \right] = 0 
\label{eq:Lxi1}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

which can be solved iteratively for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\xi}^2$
\end_inset

. The variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{\mu}^2$
\end_inset

 of the weighted mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is given by the inverse of the Fisher Information, i.e. the negative expected value of the second derivative of the log-likelihood function with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{\mu}^2
=
\frac{1}{
\sum_{i=1}^n 1 / (\sigma_i^2 + \hat{\xi}^2)
}
\label{eq:sigma1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Overdispersed compositions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "sec:compositions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

U, Th and He form a ternary system, can be plotted on a ternary diagram, and are subject to the peculiar mathematics of the ternary dataspace. The `central age' is calculated from the geometric mean composition of a U-Th-(Sm)-He dataset and is a more accurate estimator of the true age than the arithmetic mean 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

. This concept can be easily generalised to four dimensions and this section will, therefore, discuss the case of (U-Th-Sm)/He dating. Given n single grain measurements [U
\begin_inset Formula $^i$
\end_inset

, Th
\begin_inset Formula $^i$
\end_inset

, Sm
\begin_inset Formula $^i$
\end_inset

, He
\begin_inset Formula $^i$
\end_inset

] (1
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

i
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

n), the calculation of a central age involves a bijection from the four-dimensional `simplex' to a three-dimensional Euclidean logratio-space 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citep
after ""
before ""
key "aitchison1986, vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
  \label{eq:logratio-transform}
  v^i  =  ln\left(\frac{[U^i]}{[He^i]}\right),~
  w^i  =  ln\left(\frac{[Th^i]}{[He^i]}\right),~
  x^i  =  ln\left(\frac{[Sm^i]}{[He^i]}\right)
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The central age is obtained by calculating the average logratio composition (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{w}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{x}$
\end_inset

) and converting it to a geometric mean composition using the inverse logratio transformation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
  \label{eq:inverse-transform}
\begin{split}
&  \overline{U}  =  \frac{e^{\overline{v}}}{e^{\overline{v}}+e^{\overline{w}}+e^{\overline{x}}+1},~
  \overline{Th}  =  \frac{e^{\overline{w}}}{e^{\overline{v}}+e^{\overline{w}}+e^{\overline{x}}+1}\\
&  \overline{Sm}  =  \frac{e^{\overline{x}}}{e^{\overline{v}}+e^{\overline{w}}+e^{\overline{x}}+1},~
  \overline{He}  =  \frac{1}{e^{\overline{v}}+e^{\overline{w}}+e^{\overline{x}}+1}
\end{split}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

This result is then plugged into the U-Th-(Sm)-He age equation. 
\newline

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The problem of averaging the compositions is very similar to the problem of averaging the ages discussed in the previous section. Given n logratio measurements X
\begin_inset Formula $^i$
\end_inset

 and their (co)variances 
\begin_inset Formula $E^i$
\end_inset

 (1 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

 i 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

 n):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
X^i \equiv
\Biggl[
\begin{array}{c}
v^i\\
w^i\\
x^i
\end{array}
\Biggr]
\mbox{~and~}
E^i \equiv
\Biggl[
\begin{array}{ccc}
\sigma_{v^i}^{2} & cov_{v^i,w^i} & cov_{v^i,x^i} \\
cov_{v^i,w^i} & \sigma_{w^i}^{2} & cov_{w^i,x^i} \\
cov_{v^i,x^i} & cov_{w^i,x^i} & \sigma_{x^i}^{2}
\end{array}
\Biggr]
\label{eq:Ai}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

our aim is to develop an algorithm to calculate the weighted mean M and its covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M \equiv
\Biggl[
\begin{array}{c}
\overline{v}\\
\overline{w}\\
\overline{x}
\end{array}
\Biggr]
\mbox{~and~}
\Sigma \equiv
\Biggl[
\begin{array}{ccc}
\sigma^2_{\overline{v}}      & cov_{\overline{v},\overline{w}}   & cov_{\overline{v},\overline{x}}\\
cov_{\overline{v},\overline{w}}  & \sigma^2_{\overline{w}}       & cov_{\overline{w},\overline{x}}\\
cov_{\overline{v},\overline{x}}  & cov_{\overline{w},\overline{x}}   & \sigma^2_{\overline{x}}\\
\end{array}
\Biggr]
\label{eq:Abar}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In principle, the logratio covariances (E
\begin_inset Formula $^i$
\end_inset

) could be directly determined from the raw mass spectrometer measurements. In practice, however, they are calculated from the individual concentrations by linear approximation, using Equation 21 of 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

, which assumes that the errors on the individual concentrations are Normal and independently distributed. Rather than propagating the internal and external uncertainties separately, as done by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

, this section introduces a weighted mean algorithm that considers both factors simultaneously, using a multivariate generalisation of the one-dimensional maximum likelihood algorithm developed in Section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ages"

\end_inset

. First, redefine the MSWD in matrix form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
MSWD = \frac{1}{df} \sum_{i=1}^n 
(X^i-M)'[E^i]^{-1}(X^i-M)
\label{eq:MSWDc}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

where df = d 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 (n - 1) is the number of degrees of freedom of the problem, with d = 2 for (U-Th)/He and d = 3 for (U-Th-Sm)/He dating. Note that, because the variability of Sm does not contribute as much to the age dispersion as that of U and Th, it is better to use only the latter two elements for the MSWD calculation. If MSWD 
\begin_inset Formula $\gg$
\end_inset

 1, the data are overdispersed and, in analogy with Equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:norm1"

\end_inset

, we will assume that the observations come from a multivariate normal distribution of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
X^i \sim N(M, E^i + \Xi)
\label{eq:norm2}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

where M denotes the mean and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Xi$
\end_inset

 is the overdispersion. The log-likelihood is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L = - \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^n 
\left(
(X^i-\hat{M})'[E^i + \hat{\Xi}]^{-1}(X^i-\hat{M})
+ ln|E^i + \hat{\Xi}| + 3~ln(2\pi)
\right)
  \label{eq:L2}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent


\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Xi}$
\end_inset

 can be found by solving the following system of non-linear equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
& \frac{\partial L}{\partial \hat{M}}  = 
\sum_{i=1}^n [(E^i+\hat{\Xi})^{-1}(X^i-\hat{M})] = 0
\label{eq:Lmu}\\
&\frac{\partial L}{\partial \hat{\Xi}}  =
\sum_{i=1}^n [(E^i+\hat{\Xi})^{-1}(X^i-\hat{M})(X^i-\hat{M})'(E^i+\hat{\Xi})^{-1}
- (E^i+\hat{\Xi})^{-1}] = 0 
\label{eq:Lxi}
\end{align}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 of the weighted mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by inverting the Fisher Information matrix, i.e. the matrix of the negative expected values of the second derivatives of the log-likelihood function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\hat{\Sigma}
=
\Biggl[
\sum_{i=1}^n (E^i+\hat{\Xi})^{-1}
\Biggr]^{-1}
\label{eq:Sigma}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

Confidence intervals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset LatexCommand label
name "sec:ci"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Using the covariance matrix of the logratio average (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

), and performing a linear error propagation, it is straightforward to calculate the covariance matrix of the geometric mean composition (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

), evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:gamma}
\hat{\Gamma} = A'\hat{\Sigma} A
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

where A is the matrix of first derivatives of Equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:inverse-transform"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{eq:df}
A =  \Biggl[
\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{\partial U}{\partial v} & \frac{\partial Th}{\partial v} & 
\frac{\partial Sm}{\partial v} & \frac{\partial He}{\partial v}\\
\frac{\partial U}{\partial w} & \frac{\partial Th}{\partial w} & 
\frac{\partial Sm}{\partial w} & \frac{\partial He}{\partial w}\\
\frac{\partial U}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial Th}{\partial x} & 
\frac{\partial Sm}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial He}{\partial x}\\
\end{array}
\Biggr]_{\hat{M}}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

Equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma"

\end_inset

 contains an expression for the covariances of the geometric mean composition, which were omitted by 
\begin_inset LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "vermeesch2008a"

\end_inset

 but are required for a full propagation of age uncertainty. However, even the complete error propagation may be inaccurate because it is based on a first order Maclaurin series expansion of Equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:inverse-transform"

\end_inset

, which is highly non-linear. This problem can be circumvented using numerical techniques, such as the following deterministic algorithm. First, build a regular grid across the two (for U-Th-He) or three (for U-Th-Sm-He) dimensions of logratio space (Figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ci"

\end_inset

.a). Second, for each of these grid points, calculate (a) its likelihood under a normal distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

 and covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, and (b) the corresponding age. Third, calculate the Bayesian cumulative posterior distribution by ranking the numerical data in order of increasing age and computing the running sum of the likelihoods. Fourth, obtain an asymmetrical 95% confidence interval from the 2.5 and 97.5 percentiles of the posterior distribution (Figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ci"

\end_inset

.b).
\end_layout

